2.2 Bytes vs Characters

* Bytes

➡ Unit: 8 bits.
➡ Use when data is binary (images, ZIP, audio) or when you need precise control of bytes.
➡ Classes: InputStream, OutputStream, FileInputStream, FileOutputStream, BufferedInputStream,
         BufferedOutputStream.

* Characters

➡ Unit: characters (Unicode code units). Java char is UTF-16 code unit.
➡ Use for textual data (source code, CSV, plain text).
➡ Classes: Reader, Writer, FileReader, FileWriter, BufferedReader, BufferedWriter.


FileInputStream fin = new FileInputStream("pic.jpg"); // bytes
FileReader fr = new FileReader("notes.txt");          // characters

* Encoding

➡ Characters must be encoded to bytes (e.g., UTF-8).
➡ Use InputStreamReader / OutputStreamWriter to bridge between bytes and characters
  and always specify charset (e.g., StandardCharsets.UTF_8) to avoid platform-dependent bugs.

* Example: reading a UTF-8 text file:

try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(
         new InputStreamReader(new FileInputStream("notes.txt"),
         StandardCharsets.UTF_8))) {
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        System.out.println(line);
    }
}
